=== Guided Meditation: noticing the presence in the environment

So with the eyes open, which is typical of the Dzogchen approach, we can notice an object in our vision. For me it's a fire extinguisher this time. So pick an object, and just notice the presence of the object. 

Now move to another object, perhaps recognizing the consistency in that presence. 

And then just noticing the space in between you and the objects---the presence within that empty space.

So we can release all objects and just stay with that presence in the environment. It's a very subtle presence. 

And this practice entails, for about a minute or so, just like you would stay with your breathing for a minute or so, or you would stay with an object like a little rock or something for a minute, we're going to stay with this presence. 

That's a very subtle effort in just keeping with that presence in the environment. And allow it to surround the body---this presence is above and below, and all around. 

Now we can release any holding, any thoughts about this presence, and just resting in that---relaxing our consciousness into that presence to include the whole environment. 

We can even notice the spontaneity. The presence isn't going anywhere; it's not coming or going. And our whole body is presence in that sense. But we can't leave the presence. 

And freedom---enlightenment, is just this presence, purely perfect. Whatever energy is in the body right now, any of that, without labels... it is purely present. 

So kudos to you if you were able to try that out. Don't worry so much if this was not resonating, that's okay.

